# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alaska-boundary-dispute
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/141st-meridian-west] The **meridian 141° west of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/141st-meridian-west] The 141st meridian west forms a great circle with the 39th meridian east.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/141st-meridian-west] Most of the border between Alaska, United States and Yukon, Canada is defined by the meridian, meaning the western extremity of Canada lies on this meridian.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The **1911 Canadian federal election** was held on September 21, 1911, to elect members of the House of Commons of Canada of the 12th Parliament of Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The central issue was Liberal support for a proposed agreement with the United States president William Howard Taft to lower tariffs.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservative Party denounced it with claims it would weaken ties with Britain, hurt the Canadian economy and Canadian identity, and lead to American annexation of Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The idea of a Canadian Navy was also an issue.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives won, and Robert Borden became the eighth prime minister.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The election ended 15 years of government by the Liberal Party of Wilfrid Laurier.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberal government was caught up in a debate over the naval arms race between the British Empire and Germany.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Laurier attempted a compromise by starting up the Canadian Navy (now the Royal Canadian Navy) but failed to appease either the French-Canadians or English-Canadians: the former refused giving any aid, and the latter suggested sending money directly to Britain.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] After the election, the Conservatives drew up a bill for naval contributions to the British, but it was held up by a lengthy Liberal filibuster before it was passed in the House of Commons by invoking closure, only to be defeated by the Liberal-controlled Senate.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Many English Canadians in British Columbia and the Maritimes felt that Laurier was abandoning Canada's traditional links to their mother country, Great Britain.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] On the other side, the Quebec nationalist Henri Bourassa, who had earlier quit the Liberal Party over what he considered the government's pro-British policies, campaigned against Laurier in the province.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Ironically, Bourassa's attacks on Laurier in Quebec aided in the election of the Conservatives, who held policies that were more staunchly imperialist than those of the Liberals.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] In mid-1910, Laurier had attempted to kill the naval issue, which was setting English-Canadians against French-Canadians by opening talks for a reciprocity treaty with the United States.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] In January 1911, Laurier and US President William Howard Taft announced that they signed a reciprocity agreement, which they decided to pass by concurrent legislation rather than a formal treaty, as would normally have been the case.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] As such, the reciprocity agreement had to be ratified by both houses of the US Congress rather than just the US Senate, which Laurier would later regret.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The base of Liberal support shifted to Western Canada, which sought markets for its agricultural products.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The party had long been a proponent of free trade with the United States.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The protected manufacturing businesses of Central Canada were strongly against the idea.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberals, who by ideology and history had strongly supported free trade, decided to make the issue the central plank of their re-election strategy, and they negotiated a free trade agreement in natural products with the United States.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Allen argues that two speeches by American politicians gave the Conservatives the ammunition needed to arouse anti-American, pro-British sentiments, which provided the winning votes.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Speaker of the US House of Representatives was a Democrat, Champ Clark, and he declared, on the floor of the House, "I look forward to the time when the American flag will fly over every square foot of British North America up to the North Pole.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The people of Canada are of our blood and language." Clark went on to suggest in his speech that reciprocity agreement was the first step towards the end of Canada, a speech that was greeted with "prolonged applause" according to the *Congressional Record*.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The *Washington Post* reported, "Evidently, then, the Democrats generally approved of Mr.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The *Chicago Tribune*, in an editorial, condemned Clark and warned that Clark's speech might have fatally damaged the reciprocity agreement in Canada and stated, "He lets his imagination run wild like a Missouri mule on a rampage.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] A Republican Representative, William Stiles Bennet, a member of the House Foreign Relations Committee, introduced a resolution that asked the Taft administration to begin talks with Britain on how the United States might best annex Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Taft rejected the proposal and asked the committee to take a vote on the resolution, which only Bennett supported, but the Conservatives now had more ammunition.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Since Bennett, a strong protectionist, had been an opponent of the reciprocity agreement, the Canadian historian Chantal Allen suggested that Bennett had introduced his resolution deliberately to inflame Canadian opinion against the reciprocity agreement.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Clark's speech had already provoked massive outrage in Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Bennett's resolution was taken by many Canadians as more proof that the Conservatives were right that the reciprocity agreement would result in the US annexing Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The *Washington Post* noted that the effect of Clark's speech and Bennett's resolution in Canada had "roused the opponents of reciprocity in and out of Parliament to the highest pitch of excitement they have yet reached".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] English Canada's most widely read newspaper, The *Montreal Daily Star*, which had originally supported the Liberals and reciprocity, now did a *volte-face* and turned against the reciprocity agreement.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] In an editorial, it wrote, "None of us realized the inward meaning of the shrewdly framed offer of the long headed American government when we first saw it.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Contemporary accounts mentioned in the aftermath of Clark's speech that anti-Americanism was at an all-time high in Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Many American newspapers advised their readers that if they visited Canada, they should not identify themselves as American, or they could become the objects of abuse and hatred from the Canadians.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The *New York Times*, in a July 1911 report stated that Laurier was "having the fight of his career to carry reciprocity at all".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] When the reciprocity agreement was submitted by Laurier to the House of Commons for ratification by Parliament, the Conservatives waged a vigorous filibuster against the reciprocity agreement on the floor of the House.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Although the Liberals still had two years left in their mandate, they decided to call an election to settle the issue after it had aroused controversy, and Laurier was unable to break the filibuster.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Borden largely ran on a platform of opposing the reciprocity agreement under the grounds that it would "Americanize" Canada and claimed that there was a secret plan on the part of the Taft administration to annex Canada, with the reciprocity agreement being only the first step.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] To support his claims, the Conservatives produced thousands of pamphlets reproducing the speeches of Clark and Bennett, which encouraged a massive burst of anti-Americanism that was sweeping across English Canada in 1911.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Kipling wrote in his appeal to Canadians, "It is her own soul that Canada risks today.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] In British Columbia, the Conservative Party ran on the slogan "A White Canada" by playing to the fears of British Columbians who resented the increasing presence of cheap Asian labour and the resulting depression in wages.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The campaign went badly for the Liberals, however.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The powerful manufacturing interests of Toronto and Montreal switched their allegiance and financing to the Conservatives, who argued that free trade would undermine Canadian sovereignty and lead to a slow annexation of Canada by the US.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] In an editorial after Borden's victory, the *Los Angeles Times* wrote: "Their ballots have consigned to everlasting flames the bogy of annexation by the United States which Champ Clark called from the deeps.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] It was not really a wraith of anything that existed on this side of the line.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Dow Grass of Deer Island was arrested for tampering with ballot boxes leading to the Sunbury—Queen's riding's invalidation of results.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The election is often compared to the 1988 federal election, which was also fought over free trade, but the positions of the two parties were now reversed, with the Liberals against the Conservatives' trade proposals.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Conservatives dominated in Ontario, British Columbia and Manitoba.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] They also made significant gains in Quebec and Atlantic Canada, although the Liberals still won pluralities in both regions.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] The Liberals continued to dominate in Alberta and Saskatchewan, where free trade was extremely popular.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] Notably, this remains the most recent federal election where the Liberals would win the most seats in Alberta (although most Albertan Liberals supported the Borden-led Unionist government during the First World War).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] 1 One Conservative candidate was acclaimed in Ontario.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p01] 2 One Liberal candidate was acclaimed in Ontario, and two Liberals were acclaimed in Quebec.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] James William Maddin previously campaigned as a Liberal-Conservative, but lost in 1911 as a Liberal.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Carroll was the winning Liberal candidate.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Samuel John Martin campaigned as a Liberal in 1908.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Eugène-Grégoire Quesnel campaigned as an Independent in 1908.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Election had been postponed to October 12.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Henri Sévérin Béland, incumbent in Beauce, campaigned in both Beauce (won) and Montmagny (lost).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Louis-Joseph Papineau, previously elected as a Liberal in 1908, was reelected as a Conservative in 1911.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] The other Conservative candidate, Joseph-Gédéon-Horace Bergeron, had been previously elected to the House of Commons.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Rodolphe Forget, incumbent in Charlevoix, campaigned and won in both Charlevoix and Montmorency.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Rodolphe Lemieux, incumbent in Gaspé, campaigned in Gaspé (lost) and Rouville (won).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] David Arthur Lafortune was originally elected as an Independent Liberal in a 1909 byelection.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] George Frederick Hodgins, the Liberal incumbent, came in at 3rd place.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Wilfrid Laurier was also acclaimed in Quebec East.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Positive indicates improvement to standing of party winning in 1908; negative points to 2020's second-place party being swung to.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] 2nd place finisher in 1908 did not contest the 1911 election.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Winning party did not field a candidate inn 1908.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Hormidas Mayrand (Liberal) win in 1908 and lost in 1911 (both were two-way contests).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Opponents in each election were of different affiliations.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] Liberal candidate won in 1908 but lost in 1911.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1911-canadian-federal-election-p02] There were also two Independent Liberal candidates in 1908, while the Conservatives fielded a candidate only in 1911.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The **1917 Franco-Russian agreement** was a secret treaty between the French Third Republic and the Russian Empire to support one another's territorial claims in settlement following the First World War.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Under the agreement France recognised Russia's claim to any portions of Poland that she could occupy, and Russia supported France's claim for the return of Alsace–Lorraine from Germany and right to occupy other parts of Germany in the post-war period.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Formal acceptance letters between the two parties were exchanged on 10 March 1917, but the treaty had little effect as the Russian imperial government fell days later during the February Revolution.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Also, the French government of Aristide Briand fell on 20 March, and representatives of the replacement Alexandre Ribot administration agreed with the new Russian Provisional Government that the treaty had been a mistake.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] With defeat in the 1870–1871 Franco-Prussian War France had lost the territory of Alsace–Lorraine to Germany.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] A revanchist movement to recover the territory played a key role in French politics thereafter and a desire for military strength led France to enter into an alliance with the Russian Empire in the 1890s.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] That stood in opposition to the Triple Alliance of Germany, Austria-Hungary and Italy.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Russia had little interest in who controlled Alsace–Lorraine but wanted support for its ambitions in Eastern Europe and the Balkans.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Russia's western frontier had been formed during the late 18th and early 19th centuries with the partitioning of Poland between Russia, Germany and Austria-Hungary.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The First World War broke out in summer 1914; a Russian invasion of East Prussia was halted and Russian forces were afterwards gradually pushed back further into their own territory.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The Russian Brusilov Offensive of summer 1916 won back territory in Galicia and destabilised Austria-Hungary at a heavy cost in casualties.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] However, the offensive soon lost momentum, as the Russian advance was stopped by German reinforcements by the end of August.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Romania joined the war on the Russian side in August 1916, but it was defeated by German and Austro-Hungarian troops.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The Western Front where France and Britain fought Germany had remained largely static after initial German advances in Belgium and north-eastern France.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] French attempts to seize Alsace–Lorraine at the start of the war had been unsuccessful.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Nonetheless, by early 1917 the initiative was with the Allies, who planned simultaneous attack on all fronts.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Discussions between France and Russia on a post-war revision of frontiers began as early as 1915.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] High level discussions proceeded on 3 February 1917 when the French Minister of the Colonies Gaston Doumergue met with the Russian Tsar Nicholas II.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Nicholas told Doumergue that he was worried about interference in the settlement of post-war borders in Europe from US President Woodrow Wilson who he accused of carrying out "phony humanitarianism".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Nicholas argued that France needed to take steps to ensure she was supported in discussions over the border.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Doumergue reported that to the French government, and Philippe Berthelot was tasked to draft an agreement in general terms that both nations would support each other militarily, industrially and economically, without detail of the border agreement.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Russian Foreign Minister Nikolai Pokrovsky reported details of the meeting to Izvolsky and Sazonov (who was then ambassador to Britain) on 12 February.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Pokrovsky noted that Nicholas had agreed in principle and that it provided a basis to secure from France support for Russia's claim of the right to define the borders of Eastern Europe and to annul the parts of the Treaty of Paris (1856) that restricted Russian military presence on Åland.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] On 14 February Pokrovsky wrote to the French ambassador in Petrograd, Maurice Paléologue, to reiterate his support for French proposals, adding that he would support French military occupation of the western Rhine territory after the war.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Paléologue and Doumergue thought they had the authority to proceed and drafted a treaty outlining the French border proposals.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] News of that shocked the French government, which feared the reaction of its British allies if the treaty was leaked to them.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Izvolsky called at the French foreign ministry on 16 February to seek a reciprocal agreement on Russia's ambitions for Eastern Europe.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The French initially considered that the 1915 Constantinople Agreement was sufficient *quid pro quo*, but Russia insisted and relied on Berthelot's draft document that promised co-operation between the nations.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] France eventually agreed, and a secret treaty was produced that stated that in post-war settlements, Russia would recognise France's claim to Alsace–Lorraine while France would support Russia's claim to whatever portions of Poland that could be conquered.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Formal acceptance letters were exchanged on 10 March, and the following day, Izvolsky wrote to Pokrovsky and stated that France had recognised Russia's complete independence in establishing its future Western frontier.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The agreement did not survive the February Revolution in Russia (8–16 March 1917) and became one of the last acts of Nicholas' government.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] After the 15 March abdication of Nicholas II, the Russian Provisional Government on 29 March declared its support for the creation of an independent Polish state in all areas where Poles comprised the majority of the population.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The French government of Aristide Briand fell on 20 March, and details of the treaty remained generally unknown until a parliamentary inquest unearthed them some months later.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The Provisional Government's foreign minister, Pavel Milyukov, described the agreement as a mistake, and the new French prime minister, Alexandre Ribot, indicated his agreement.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] By June, the French demands for the post-war settlement extended only to the return of Alsace–Lorraine and the payment of reparations by the Central Powers.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The entry of the United States into the war in April 1917 and the ongoing political and military collapse of Russia saw the Western Allies come around to the idea of an independent Poland as a means of embarrassing Germany.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] On 26 April the British chancellor of the exchequer, Andrew Bonar Law, publicly stated the government's support on the matter.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] In June, the French government formally recognised the Blue Army as the Polish national army.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The British government regarded the proposed neutral Rhineland state as a mistake that would cause instability in Western Europe.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Its policy was instead to rely on the threat of American power as a counter to future German militarism.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] British Foreign Secretary Arthur Balfour declared on 19 December 1917 that his government had never supported the French ambitions for an independent Rhineland.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Towards the end of the war, with an Allied victory in sight, on 3 November 1918 the independent Second Polish Republic was proclaimed.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The post-war settlement between the Allies and Germany, the 1919 Treaty of Versailles, defined the Polish western border with Germany.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The eastern border was proposed by the newly founded League of Nations to lie on the Curzon Line.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] Polish ambitions for further territory led to the Polish–Soviet War and to the Treaty of Riga with the Soviet Union securing more land to the east.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The Allied forces occupied the Rhineland after the war until 1930, and the Rhineland remained demilitarised until it was reoccupied by German troops in 1936.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] In response to German refusals to pay reparations that were due under the Treaty of Versailles, French and Belgian troops occupied the Ruhr region between 1923 and 1925.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] The Treaty of Versailles also placed Saarland under a League of Nations mandate as the Territory of the Saar Basin from 1920 that was policed by Allied and neutral troops.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/1917-franco-russian-agreement] In 1935, the region returned Germany after a plebiscite massively supported German rule.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The **56th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 56 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] It crosses Europe, Asia, the Pacific Ocean, North America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 17 hours, 37 minutes during the summer solstice and 6 hours, 57 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The **57th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 57 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 17 hours, 53 minutes during the summer solstice and 6 hours, 43 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] On June 21, the sun is at 56.44 degrees in the sky and on December 21, the sun is at 9.56 degrees in the sky.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] During the summer solstice, nighttime does not get beyond nautical twilight, a condition which lasts throughout the month of June.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] It is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day of the month of April.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 18.00º in October and > 11.00º in November.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The only capital city on the 57th parallel north is Riga.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The **58th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 58 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude the Sun is visible for 18 hours, 11 minutes during the summer solstice and 6 hours, 27 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] In general, this parallel sees significant differences in temperature and precipitation with proximity to warm ocean currents.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The moderation from the Gulf Stream ensures a moderate oceanic climate in much of Western Europe and on the immediate coastline of Alaska, whereas moving inland on continental masses, subarctic climates predominate as the dark winters dominate the temperature cycle.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] In the transitional area centred on the Baltic Sea this latitude sees a humid continental climate with warm summers and snowy winters somewhat below freezing.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] Where cold ocean currents dominate such as near Hudson Bay the climate is polar, rendering in severe winter conditions and very subdued summers.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] This type of climate is seen in the surroundings of Inukjuak in Quebec, Canada, where the sea ice eliminates winter moderation, but the thawing of the cold water renders in very cool summers as well.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] In more continental cold areas such as these winters commonly go below −30 °C or −22 °F even during the day.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] Further west in inland areas winters are often as severe, but summers average above 22 °C or 71.6 °F, similar to the Baltic region where climates are much gentler.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The **59th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 59 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude the Sun is visible for 18 hours, 30 minutes during the summer solstice and 6 hours, 11 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] If latitude in northern hemisphere is 59°45′ or smaller, every day in August can view both nautical dawn and nautical dusk.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The **60th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 60 degrees north of Earth's equator.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] In Canada, the 60th parallel forms the southern mainland boundary of the northern territories of Yukon, Northwest Territories, and Nunavut with the western provinces of British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] Accordingly, "north of 60" is an expression often used for the territories.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The 60th Parallel Territorial Park is on Mackenzie Highway between Alberta and Northwest Territories and it has a visitor centre there in the homeland of the Yellowknives Dene First Nation and the North Slave Métis Alliance.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] Between 1776 and 1950, the 60th parallel formed the southern limit of the Royal Greenland Trade Department's exclusive monopoly on trade near the Dano-Norwegian and later Danish colonies of Greenland (1776–1782) and South Greenland (1782–1950).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] Although it lies approximately twice as far away from the Equator as from the North Pole, the 60th parallel is half as long as the Equator line, due to the cosine of 60 degrees being 0.5.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] This is where the Earth bulges halfway as much as on the Equator.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude, the Sun is visible for 18 hours, 52 minutes during the June solstice and 5 hours, 52 minutes during the December solstice.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The maximum altitude of the Sun is 53.44° on 21 June and 6.56° on 21 December.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 15.00º in October and > 8.00º in November.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] The lowest latitude where white nights can be observed is approximately on this parallel.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] It is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day between August 22 and April 21.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/56th-parallel-north] Malachy Tallack wrote a book, *Sixty Degrees North: Around the World in Search of Home*, about his travels along the general line of the parallel, starting and finishing at Shetland.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] The number of abortion clinics in Alaska has been declining, going from fourteen in 1982 to thirteen in 1992 to three in 2014.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] 1,547 abortions took place in Alaska in 2014, and 1,459 took place in 2015.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] There is state funding for abortions based on income.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska, California, and New Hampshire did not voluntarily provide the Center for Disease Control with abortion related data in 2000 or 2001.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2014, a poll by the Pew Research Center reported that 63% of adults in the state of Alaska believe abortion should be legal in all or most cases, with 34% stating it should be illegal in all or most cases.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska, Hawaii, Washington, and New York were the only four states that made abortion legal between 1967 and 1970 that did not require a reason to request an abortion.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 1970, the state repealed some of its abortion laws, along with Hawaii, New York, and Washington.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] The following year, Alaska repealed its statute that said inducing an abortion was a criminal offense.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] State law still required in 1971 that any woman getting a legal abortion in the state needed to be a resident for some specific period between 30 and 90 days.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Some states, such as Alaska, Mississippi, West Virginia, Texas, and Kansas, have passed laws requiring abortion providers to warn patients of a link between abortion and breast cancer, and to issue other scientifically unsupported warnings.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] The state was one of 23 states in 2007 to have a detailed abortion-specific informed consent requirement.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska and Minnesota both require that women seeking abortions after 20 weeks be informed that, while experts disagree on the issue of whether or not a fetus can feel pain at 20 weeks, it is possible.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] House Bill 250 was introduced in 2017 by Rep.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] The bill was called the "Life at Conception Act", and it never made it out of committee in Alaska's House.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2017, Washington State, New Mexico, Illinois, Alaska, Maryland, Massachusetts, Connecticut, and New Jersey allow, by state law qualified non-physicians to prescribe drugs for medical abortions only.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In May 2019, Eastman introduced House Bill 178, which defines abortion as "murder of an unborn child"; the bill was never heard before a committee.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2022, Governor Mike Dunleavy expressed interest in an amendment to the Alaska Constitution clarifying the legality of abortion in the state.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] 2022 happened to be the year that Alaska's regularly scheduled ballot question for calling a state constitutional convention was asked.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Dunleavy and other anti-abortion advocates recommended voting "yes", but the question was resoundingly defeated, with 70% voting "no".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2023, the bipartisan coalition majority in the Alaska State Senate is consensus-focused and unlikely to address controversial topics like abortion.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] The US Supreme Court's decision in 1973's *Roe v.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Wade* ruling meant the state could no longer regulate abortion in the first trimester.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 1997, the Alaska Supreme Court ruled in *Valley Hospital Association, Inc. v.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Mat-Su Coalition for Choice* that the privacy clause of the Alaska Constitution protects the right to an abortion.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] This ruling remains in effect after the US Supreme Court overruled Roe v.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2016, the Alaska Supreme Court struck down a parental notification law that had been established in 2010.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In September 2024, an Alaska superior court judge struck down the requirement that only licensed physicians provide abortions, meaning that the procedure can now also be legally performed by nurse practitioners and physician assistants.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Between 1982 and 1992, the number of abortion clinics in the state decreased by 1, going from 14 in 1982 to 13 in 1992.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2014, there were 3 abortion clinics in the state.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] 90% of the boroughs in the state did not have an abortion clinic.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] That year, 37% of women in the state aged 15–44 lived in a borough without an abortion clinic.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In March 2016, there were 4 Planned Parenthood clinics in the state.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] There were still 4 Planned Parenthood clinics the following year, all of which offered abortion services, in a state with a population of 167,815 women aged 15–49.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2022, there were three Planned Parenthood clinics in the state.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2024, there were two Planned Parenthood clinics.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 1990, 69,000 women in the state faced the risk of an unintended pregnancy.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2013, among white women aged 15–19, there were 130 abortions, 10 abortions for black women aged 15–19, 20 abortions for Hispanic women aged 15–19, and 70 abortions for women of all other races.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2017, the state had an infant mortality rate of 5.6 deaths per 1,000 live births.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] 17 US states, including Alaska, use their own funds to cover all or most "medically necessary" abortions sought by low-income women under Medicaid, 13 of which are required by State court orders to do so.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] In 2010, the state had 835 publicly funded abortions, all of which were state funded.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Women from the state participated in marches supporting abortion rights as part of a #StoptheBans movement in May 2019.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Hundreds of women attended a rally in Anchorage at Town Square Park to protest legislation proposed in Alaska's House to restrict abortion rights.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] The event was organized by Planned Parenthood Votes and Alaska ACLU.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] There was another rally at the Alaska Capitol in Juneau in May 2019, in opposition to the bill proposed by Republican Rep.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Following the leak of the overturning of Roe v.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] Wade on May 2, 2022, Alaska saw abortion rights protests in Anchorage, Fairbanks, and Haines.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] David Eastman (R-Wasilla) was censured by the Alaska Legislature in 2017 after he claimed that women used Medicaid support for abortion as a "free trip to the city".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/abortion-in-alaska] A small counter-protest was organized by anti-abortion rights activists at the Alaska Capitol in Juneau in May 2019, in support of proposed restrictions on women's ability to access legal abortions in the state.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The first capital of Acadia was established in 1605 as Port-Royal.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Soon after, English forces of Captain Argall, an English ship's captain employed by the Virginia Company of London attacked and burned down the fortified habitation in 1613.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] A new centre for Port-Royal was established nearby, and it remained the longest-serving capital of French Acadia until the British siege of Port Royal in 1710.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] There were six colonial wars in a 74-year period in which British interests tried to capture Acadia, starting with King William's War in 1689.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] French troops from Quebec, Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy, and French priests continually raided New England settlements along the border in Maine during these wars.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Acadia was conquered in 1710 during Queen Anne's War, while New Brunswick and much of Maine remained contested territory.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Prince Edward Island (Île Saint-Jean) and Cape Breton (Île Royale) remained under French control, as agreed under Article XIII of the Treaty of Utrecht.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The English took control of Maine by defeating the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French priests during Father Rale's War.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During King George's War, France and New France made significant attempts to regain mainland Nova Scotia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The British took New Brunswick in Father Le Loutre's War, and they took Île Royale and Île Saint-Jean in 1758 following the French and Indian War.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The territory was eventually divided into British colonies.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The term Acadia today refers to regions of North America that are historically associated with the lands, descendants, or culture of the former region.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] It particularly refers to regions of the Maritimes with Acadian roots, language, and culture, primarily in New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, the Magdalen Islands and Prince Edward Island, as well as in Maine.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] "Acadia" can also refer to the Acadian diaspora in southern Louisiana, a region also referred to as Acadiana since the early 1960s.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In the abstract, Acadia refers to the existence of an Acadian culture in any of these regions.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] People living in Acadia are called Acadians, which in Louisiana changed to Cajuns, the more common, rural American, name of Acadians.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Explorer Giovanni da Verrazzano is credited for originating the designation Acadia on his 16th-century map, where he applied the ancient Greek name "Arcadia" to the entire Atlantic coast north of Virginia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] "Arcadia" is derived from the Arcadia region in Greece, which had the extended meanings of "refuge" or "idyllic place".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Henry IV of France chartered a colony south of the St.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Lawrence River between the 40th and 46th parallels in 1603, and he recognized it as *La Cadie*.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Samuel de Champlain fixed its present orthography with the *r* omitted, and cartographer William Francis Ganong has shown its gradual progress northeastwards to its resting place in the Atlantic provinces of Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] As an alternative theory, some historians suggest that the name is derived from the indigenous Canadian Mi'kmaw language, in which Cadie means "fertile land".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The history of Acadia was significantly influenced by the great power conflict between France and England, later Great Britain, that occurred in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Prior to the arrival of Europeans, the Mi'kmaq had been living in Acadia for at least two to three thousand years.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Early European settlers were French subjects primarily from the Poitou-Charentes and Aquitaine regions of southwestern France, now known as Nouvelle-Aquitaine.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The first French settlement was established by Pierre Dugua de Mons, Governor of Acadia, under the authority of the French King, Henri IV, on Saint Croix Island in 1604.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The following year, the settlement was moved across the Bay of Fundy to Port Royal after a difficult winter on the island and deaths from scurvy.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] There, they constructed a new habitation.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1607, the colony received bad news as Henri IV revoked Sieur de Mons' royal fur monopoly, citing that the income was insufficient to justify supplying the colony further.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Thus recalled, the last of the French left Port Royal in August 1607.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Their allies, the Mi'kmaq, agreed to act as custodians of the settlement.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] When the former lieutenant governor, Jean de Biencourt de Poutrincourt et de Saint-Just, returned in 1610, he found the Port Royal habitation just as it was left.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During the first 80 years of the French presence in Acadia, there were numerous significant battles as the English, Scottish, and Dutch contested the French for possession of the colony.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] These battles happened at Port Royal, Saint John, Cap de Sable (present-day Port La Tour, Nova Scotia), Jemseg, Castine, and Baleine.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] From the 1680s onward, there were six colonial wars that took place in the region (see the French and Indian Wars as well as Father Rale's War and Father Le Loutre's War).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] These wars were fought between New England and New France, and their respective native allies.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The wars were fought on two fronts: the southern border of Acadia, which New France defined as the Kennebec River in southern Maine and in present-day peninsular Nova Scotia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The latter involved preventing the British from taking the capital of Acadia, Port Royal (See Queen Anne's War), establishing themselves at Canso (See Father Rale's War) and founding Halifax (see Father Le Loutre's War).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] From 1640 to 1645, Acadia was plunged into what some historians have described as a civil war.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The war was between Port Royal, where the Governor of Acadia Charles de Menou d'Aulnay de Charnisay was stationed, and present-day Saint John, New Brunswick, where Governor of Acadia Charles de Saint-Étienne de la Tour was stationed.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] There were four major battles in the war, and d'Aulnay ultimately prevailed over La Tour.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During King Philip's War (1675–78), the governor was absent from Acadia (having first been imprisoned in Boston during the Dutch occupation of Acadia) and Jean-Vincent d'Abbadie de Saint-Castin was established at the capital of Acadia, Pentagouêt.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] From there he worked with the Abenaki of Acadia to raid British settlements migrating over the border of Acadia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] British retaliation included attacking deep into Acadia in the Battle of Port La Tour (1677).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In response to King Philip's War in New England, the native peoples in Acadia joined the Wabanaki Confederacy to form a political and military alliance with New France.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Confederacy remained significant military allies to New France through six wars.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Until the French and Indian War the Wabanaki Confederacy remained the dominant military force in the region.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] There were tensions on the border between New England and Acadia, which New France defined as the Kennebec River in southern Maine.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] English settlers from Massachusetts (whose charter included the Maine area) had expanded their settlements into Acadia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During King William's War (1688–97), some Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French Priests participated in defending Acadia at its border with New England, which New France defined as the Kennebec River in southern Maine.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Toward this end, the members of the Wabanaki Confederacy, on the Saint John River and in other places, joined the New France expedition against present-day Bristol, Maine (the siege of Pemaquid (1689)), Salmon Falls and present-day Portland, Maine.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In response, the New Englanders retaliated by attacking Port Royal and present-day Guysborough.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1694, the Wabanaki Confederacy participated in the Raid on Oyster River at present-day Durham, New Hampshire.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Two years later, New France, led by Pierre Le Moyne d'Iberville, returned and fought a naval battle in the Bay of Fundy before moving on to raid Bristol, Maine, again.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In retaliation, the New Englanders, led by Benjamin Church, engaged in a Raid on Chignecto (1696) and the siege of the Capital of Acadia at Fort Nashwaak.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] At the end of the war England returned the territory to France in the Treaty of Ryswick and the borders of Acadia remained the same.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During Queen Anne's War, some Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French priests participated again in defending Acadia at its border with New England.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] They made numerous raids on New England settlements along the border in the Northeast Coast Campaign and the famous Raid on Deerfield.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In retaliation, Major Benjamin Church went on his fifth and final expedition to Acadia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] He raided present-day Castine, Maine and continued with raids against Grand Pre, Pisiquid, and Chignecto.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] A few years later, defeated in the siege of Pemaquid (1696), Captain March made an unsuccessful siege on the Capital of Acadia, Port Royal (1707).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] British forces were successful with the siege of Port Royal (1710), while the Wabanaki Confederacy were successful in the nearby Battle of Bloody Creek (1711) and continued raids along the Maine frontier.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The 1710 conquest of the Acadian capital of Port Royal during the war was confirmed by the Treaty of Utrecht of 1713.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The British conceded to the French "the island called Cape Breton, as also all others, both in the mouth of the river of St.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Lawrence, and in the gulph of the same name", and "all manner of liberty to fortify any place or places there." The French established a fortress at Louisbourg, Cape Breton, to guard the sea approaches to Quebec.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] On 23 June 1713, the French residents of Nova Scotia were given one year to declare allegiance to Britain or leave the region.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In the meantime, the French signalled their preparedness for future hostilities by beginning the construction of Fortress Louisbourg on Île Royale, now Cape Breton Island.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The British grew increasingly alarmed by the prospect of disloyalty in wartime of the Acadians now under their rule.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] French missionaries worked to maintain the loyalty of Acadians, and to maintain a hold on the mainland part of Acadia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During the escalation that preceded Dummer's War (1722–1725), some Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French priests persisted in defending Acadia, which had been conceded to the British in the Treaty of Utrecht, at its border against New England.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Miꞌkmaq refused to recognize the treaty handing over their land to the English and hostilities resumed.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Miꞌkmaq raided the new fort at Canso, Nova Scotia in 1720.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Confederacy made numerous raids on New England settlements along the border into New England.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Towards the end of January 1722, Governor Samuel Shute chose to launch a punitive expedition against Sébastien Rale, a Jesuit missionary, at Norridgewock.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] This breach of the border of Acadia, which had at any rate been ceded to the British, drew all of the tribes of the Wabanaki Confederacy into the conflict.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Under potential siege by the Confederacy, in May 1722, Lieutenant Governor John Doucett took 22 Miꞌkmaq hostage at Annapolis Royal to prevent the capital from being attacked.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In July 1722, the Abenaki and Miꞌkmaq created a blockade of Annapolis Royal, with the intent of starving the capital.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The natives captured 18 fishing vessels and prisoners from present-day Yarmouth to Canso.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] They also seized prisoners and vessels from the Bay of Fundy.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] As a result of the escalating conflict, Massachusetts Governor Shute officially declared war on 22 July 1722.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The first battle of Father Rale's War happened in the Nova Scotia theatre.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In response to the blockade of Annapolis Royal, at the end of July 1722, New England launched a campaign to end the blockade and retrieve over 86 New England prisoners taken by the natives.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] One of these operations resulted in the Battle at Jeddore.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Then in July 1724 a group of sixty Miꞌkmaq and Wolastoqiyik raided Annapolis Royal.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] As a result of Father Rale's War, present-day central Maine fell again to the British with the defeat of Sébastien Rale at Norridgewock and the subsequent retreat of the native population from the Kennebec and Penobscot rivers.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] King George's War began when the war declarations from Europe reached the French fortress at Louisbourg first, on May 3, 1744, and the forces there wasted little time in beginning hostilities.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Concerned about their overland supply lines to Quebec, they first raided the British fishing port of Canso on May 23, and then organized an attack on Annapolis Royal, then the capital of Nova Scotia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] However, French forces were delayed in departing Louisbourg, and their Miꞌkmaq and Wolastoqey allies decided to attack on their own in early July.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Annapolis had received news of the war declaration, and was somewhat prepared when the Indians began besieging Fort Anne.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Lacking heavy weapons, the Indians withdrew after a few days.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Then, in mid-August, a larger French force arrived before Fort Anne, but was also unable to mount an effective attack or siege against the garrison, which had received supplies and reinforcements from Massachusetts.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1745, British colonial forces conducted the siege of Port Toulouse (St.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Peter's) and then captured Fortress Louisbourg after a siege of six weeks.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] France launched a major expedition to recover Acadia in 1746.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Beset by storms, disease, and finally the death of its commander, the Duc d'Anville, it returned to France in tatters without reaching its objective.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] French officer Jean-Baptiste Nicolas Roch de Ramezay also arrived from Quebec and conducted the Battle at Port-la-Joye on Île Saint-Jean and the Battle of Grand Pré.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Despite the British capture of the Acadian capital in the siege of Port Royal (1710), Nova Scotia remained primarily occupied by Catholic Acadians and Miꞌkmaq.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] To prevent the establishment of Protestant settlements in the region, Miꞌkmaq raided the early British settlements of present-day Shelburne (1715) and Canso (1720).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] A generation later, Father Le Loutre's War began when Edward Cornwallis arrived to establish Halifax with 13 transports on 21 June 1749.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The British quickly began to build other settlements.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] To guard against Miꞌkmaq, Acadian and French attacks on the new Protestant settlements, they erected fortifications in Halifax (Citadel Hill) (1749), Dartmouth (1750), Bedford (Fort Sackville) (1751), Lunenburg (1753) and Lawrencetown (1754).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] There were numerous Miꞌkmaq and Acadian raids on these villages such as the Raid on Dartmouth (1751).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Within 18 months of establishing Halifax, the British also took firm control of peninsular Nova Scotia by building fortifications in all the major Acadian communities: present-day Windsor (Fort Edward, 1750); Grand Pre (Fort Vieux Logis, 1749) and Chignecto (Fort Lawrence, 1750).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] (A British fort already existed at the other major Acadian centre of Annapolis Royal, Nova Scotia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Cobequid remained without a fort.) Numerous Miꞌkmaq and Acadian raids took place against these fortifications, such as the siege of Grand Pre (1749).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In the years after the British conquest, the Acadians refused to swear unconditional oaths of allegiance to the British crown.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During this time period some Acadians participated in militia operations against the British and maintained vital supply lines to Fortress Louisbourg and Fort Beausejour.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During the French and Indian War, the British sought to neutralize any military threat Acadians posed and to interrupt the vital supply lines Acadians provided to Louisbourg by deporting them.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] This process began in 1755, after the British captured Fort Beauséjour and began the expulsion of the Acadians with the Bay of Fundy Campaign.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Between six and seven thousand Acadians were expelled from Nova Scotia to the lower British American colonies.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Some Acadians eluded capture by fleeing deep into the wilderness or into French-controlled Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Quebec town of L'Acadie (now a sector of Saint-Jean-sur-Richelieu) was founded by expelled Acadians.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] After the siege of Louisbourg (1758), a second wave of the expulsion began with the St.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] John River Campaign, Petitcodiac River Campaign, Gulf of St.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Lawrence Campaign and the Île Saint-Jean Campaign.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Acadians and the Wabanaki Confederacy put up a significant resistance to the British throughout the war.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] They repeatedly raided Canso, Lunenburg, Halifax, Chignecto and into New England.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Any pretense that France might maintain or regain control over the remnants of Acadia came to an end with the fall of Montreal in 1760 and the 1763 Treaty of Paris, which permanently ceded almost all of eastern New France to Britain.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1763, Britain would designate lands west of the Appalachians as the "Indian Reserve", but did not respect Miꞌkmaq title to the Atlantic region, claiming title was obtained from the French.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Miꞌkmaq remain in Acadia to this day.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In Louisiana, the demonym *Acadian* developed into *Cadien*, anglicized as *Cajun,* which was first used as a pejorative term until its later mainstream acceptance.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Britain eventually moderated its policies and allowed Acadians to return to Nova Scotia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] However, most of the fertile former Acadian lands were now occupied by British colonists.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The returning Acadians settled instead in more outlying areas of the original Acadia, such as Cape Breton and the areas which are now New Brunswick and Prince Edward Island.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Among the Acadian descendants in the Canadian Maritime provinces, there was a revival of cultural awareness which is recognized as an Acadian Renaissance, with a struggle for recognition of Acadians as a distinct group starting in the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Some Acadian deputies were elected to legislative assemblies, starting in 1836 with Simon d'Entremont in Nova Scotia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Several other provincial and federal members followed in New Brunswick and in Prince Edward Island.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] This period saw the founding of Acadian higher educational institutions: the Saint Thomas Seminary from 1854 to 1862 and then Saint Joseph's College from 1864, both in Memramcook, New Brunswick.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] This was followed by the founding of Acadian newspapers: the weekly *Le Moniteur Acadien* in 1867 and the daily *L'Évangéline* in 1887 (fr), named after the epic poem by Longfellow.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In New Brunswick the 1870s saw a struggle against the Common Schools Act of 1871, which imposed a non-denominational school system and forbade religious instruction during school hours.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] This led to widespread Acadian protests and school-tax boycotts, culminating in the 1875 riots in the town of Caraquet.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Finally in 1875 a compromise was reached allowing for some Catholic religious teaching in the schools.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In the 1880s there began a series of Acadian national conventions.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The first in 1881 adopted Assumption Day (Aug.15) as the Acadian national holiday.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The convention favored the argument of the priest Marcel-François Richard (fr) that Acadians are a distinct people which should have a national holiday distinct from that of Quebec (Saint-Jean-Baptiste Day).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The second convention in 1884 adopted other national symbols including the flag of Acadia designed by Marcel-François Richard, and the anthem Ave maris stella.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The third convention in 1890 created the Société nationale L'Assomption to promote the interests of the Acadian people in the Maritimes.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Other Acadian national conventions continued until the fifteenth in 1972.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1885, the author, historian and linguist Pascal Poirier became the first Acadian member of the Senate of Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] By the early twentieth century, some Acadians were chosen for leadership positions in New Brunswick.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1912, Monseigneur Édouard LeBlanc of Nova Scotia was named bishop of Saint John, after a campaign lasting many years to convince the Vatican to appoint an Acadian bishop.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1917, the premier of Prince Edward Island resigned to accept a judicial position, and his Conservative Party chose Aubin-Edmond Arsenault as successor until the next election in 1919.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Arsenault thus became the first Acadian provincial premier of any province in Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1923, Peter Veniot became the first Acadian premier of New Brunswick when he was chosen by the Liberal Party to complete the term of the retiring premier until 1925.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The expansion of Acadian influence in the Catholic church continued in 1936 with the creation of the Archdiocese of Moncton whose first archbishop was Louis-Joseph-Arthur Melanson, and whose Cathédrale Notre-Dame de l’Assomption was completed in 1940.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The new archdiocese was expanded to include new predominantly Acadian dioceses in Bathurst, New Brunswick (1938), in Edmundston (1944) and in Yarmouth, Nova Scotia (1953).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1960, Louis Robichaud became the first Acadian to be elected premier of a Canadian province.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] He was elected premier of New Brunswick in 1960 and served three terms until 1970.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Robichaud government created the Université de Moncton in 1963 as a unilingual French-language university, corresponding to the much older unilingual English-language University of New Brunswick.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1964, two different deputy ministers of education were named to direct English-language and French-language school systems respectively.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In the next few years, the Université de Moncton absorbed the former Saint-Joseph's College, as well as the École Normale (teacher's college) which trained French-speaking teachers for the Acadian schools.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1977, two French-speaking colleges in Northern New Brunswick were transformed into the Edmundston and Shippagan campuses of the Université de Moncton.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The New Brunswick Equal Opportunity program of 1967 introduced reforms of municipal structures, of health care, of education, and of the administration of justice.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In general, these changes tended to reduce economic inequality between regions of the province, and therefore tended to favour the disadvantaged Acadian regions.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The New Brunswick Official Languages Act (1969) declared New Brunswick officially bilingual with English and French having equal status as official languages.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Residents have the right to receive provincial government services in the official language of their choice.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The New Brunswick government of Richard Hatfield (1970–87) cooperated with the Government of Canada in including the right to linguistic equality in the province as a part of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms of 1982, so that it cannot be rescinded by any future provincial government.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Nova Scotia adopted Bill 65 in 1981 to give Acadian schools legal status, and also created a study program including Acadian history and culture.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Acadian schools were placed under separate management in 1996.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Prince Edward Island provided French-language schools in 1980 in areas with a sufficient number of Acadian students, followed by a French-language school commission for the province in 1990.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 2000 a decision of the Supreme Court of Canada obliged the provincial government to build French schools at least in Charlottetown and Summerside, the two largest communities.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The new French-language daily newspaper L'Acadie Nouvelle published in Caraquet appeared in 1984, replacing L’Évangeline which ceased publication in 1982.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The series of Acadian National Conventions from 1881 to 1972 was followed by an Acadian National Orientation Convention in 1979 at Edmundston.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Since 1994, there has been a new series of Acadian World Congresses at five-year intervals starting with 1994 in southeastern New Brunswick and 1999 in Louisiana.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The most recent was centered in Summerside, Prince Edward Island in 2019.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During much of the 17th and early 18th centuries, Norridgewock on the Kennebec River and Castine at the end of the Penobscot River were the southernmost settlements of Acadia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The French government defined the borders of Acadia as roughly between the 40th and 46th parallels on the Atlantic coast.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The following list includes those who were born in Acadia (yet not necessarily of Acadian ethnicity) or those who became naturalized citizens prior to the fall of the French in the region in 1763.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Those who came for brief periods from other countries are not included (e.g.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] John Gorham, Edward Cornwallis, James Wolfe, Boishébert, etc.).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Acadia was in territory disputed between France and Great Britain.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Although France controlled the territory in the remaining periods, French monarchs consistently neglected Acadia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Civil government under the French regime was held by a series of Governors (see List of governors of Acadia).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The government of New France was in Quebec, but it had only nominal authority over the Acadians.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Acadians implemented village self-rule.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Even after Canada had given up its elected spokesmen, the Acadians continued to demand a say in their own government, as late as 1706 petitioning the monarchy to allow them to elect spokesmen each year by a plurality of voices.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In a sign of his indifference to the colony, Louis XV agreed to their demand.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] This representative assembly was a direct offshoot of a government system that developed out of the seigneurial and church parish imported from Europe.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The seigneurial system was a "set of legal regimes and practices pertaining to local landholding, politics, economics, and jurisprudence." Many of the French governors of Acadia prior to Hector d'Andigné de Grandfontaine held seigneuries in Acadia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] As Seigneur, in addition to the power held as governor, they held the right to grant land, collect their seigneurial rents, and act in judgement over disputes within their domain.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] After Acadia came under direct Royal rule under Grandfontaine the Seigneurs continued to fulfill governance roles.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Acadian seignuerial system came to an end when the British Crown bought the seigneurial rights in the 1730s.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Catholic parish system along with the accompanying parish priest also aided in the development Acadian self-government.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Priests, given their respected position, often assisted the community in representation with the civil government at Port Royal/Annapolis Royal.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Within each parish the Acadians used the elected *marguilliers* (wardens) of the *conseil de fabrique* to administer more than just the churches' affairs in the parishes.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Acadians extended this system to see to the administrative needs of the community in general.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Acadians occupied a borderland region of the British and French empires.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] As such the Acadian homeland was subjected to the ravages of war on numerous occasions.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Through experience the Acadians learned to distrust imperial authorities (British and French).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] This is evidenced in a small way when Acadians were uncooperative with census takers.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Administrators complained of constant in-fighting among the population, which filed many petty civil suits with colonial magistrates.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Most of these were over boundary lines, as the Acadians were very quick to protect their new lands.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] After 1710, the British military administration continued to utilize the deputy system the Acadians had developed under French colonial rule.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Prior to 1732 the deputies were appointed by the governor from men in the districts of Acadian families "as ancientest and most considerable in Lands & possessions,".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] This appears to be in contravention of various British penal laws which made it nearly impossible for Roman Catholics and Protestant recusants to hold military and government positions.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The need for effective administration and communication in many of the British colonies trumped the laws.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1732, the governance institution was formalized.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Under the formalized system the colony was divided into eight districts.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Annually on October 11 free elections were to take place where each district, depending on its size, was to elect two, three, or four deputies.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In observance of the Lord's Day, if October 11 fell on a Sunday the elections were to take place on the immediately following Monday.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Notice of the annual election was to be given in all districts thirty days before the election date.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Immediately following election, deputies, both outgoing and incoming, were to report to Annapolis Royal to receive the governor's approval and instructions.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Prior to 1732 deputies had complained about the time and expense of holding office and carrying out their duties.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Under the new elected deputy system each district was to provide for the expenses of their elected deputies.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In addition to deputies, several other public positions existed.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Each district had a clerk who worked closely with the deputies and under his duties recorded the records and orders of government, deeds and conveyances, and kept other public records.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] With the rapid expansion of the Acadian populace, there was also a growing number of cattle and sheep.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The burgeoning herds and flocks, often free-ranging, necessitated the creation of the position of Overseer of Flocks.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] These individuals controlled where the flocks grazed, settled disputes and recorded the names of individuals slaughtering animals to ensure proper ownership.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Skins and hides were inspected for brands.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] After the purchase by the British Crown of the seigniorial rights in Acadia, various rents and fees were due to the Crown.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In the Minas, Piziquid and Cobequid Districts the seigniorial fees were collected by the "Collector & Receiver of All His Majesty's Quit Rents, Dues, or Revenues".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Collector was to keep a record of all rents and other fees collected, submit the rents to Annapolis Royal, and retain fifteen percent to cover his expenses.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Before 1654, trading companies and patent holders concerned with fishing recruited men in France to come to Acadia to work at the commercial outposts.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The original Acadian population was a small number of indentured servants and soldiers brought by the fur-trading companies.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Gradually, fishermen began settling in the area as well, rather than return to France with the seasonal fishing fleet.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The majority of the recruiting took place at La Rochelle.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Between 1653 and 1654, 104 men were recruited at La Rochelle.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Of these, 31% were builders, 15% were soldiers and sailors, 8% were food preparers, 6.7% were farm workers, and an additional 6.7% worked in the clothing trades.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Fifty-five percent of Acadia's first families came from western and southwestern France, primarily from Poitou, Aquitaine, Angoumois, and Saintonge.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Over 85% of these (47% of the total), were former residents of the La Chaussée area of Poitou.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Many of the families who arrived in 1632 with Isaac de Razilly shared some blood ties; those not related by blood shared cultural ties with the others.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The number of original immigrants was very small, and only about 100 surnames existed within the Acadian community.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Many of the earliest French settlers in Acadia intermarried with the local Mi'kmaq tribe.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] A Parisian lawyer, Marc Lescarbot, who spent just over a year in Acadia, arriving in May 1606, described the Micmac as having "courage, fidelity, generosity, and humanity, and their hospitality is so innate and praiseworthy that they receive among them every man who is not an enemy.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Most of the immigrants to Acadia were poor peasants in France, making them social equals in this new context.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Unlike the French colonists in Canada and the early English colonies in Plymouth and Jamestown, Acadians maintained an extended kinship system, and the large extended families assisted in building homes and barns, as well as cultivating and harvesting crops.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] They also relied on interfamily cooperation to accomplish community goals, such as building dikes to reclaim tidal marshes.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Marriages were generally not love matches but were arranged for economic or social reasons.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Parental consent was required for anyone under 25 who wished to marry, and both the mother's and father's consent was recorded in the marriage deed.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Divorce was not permitted in New France, and annulments were almost impossible to get.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Legal separation was offered as an option but was seldom used.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Acadians were suspicious of outsiders and on occasion did not readily cooperate with census takers.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The first reliable population figures for the area came with the census of 1671, which noted fewer than 450 people.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] By 1714, the Acadian population had expanded to 2,528 individuals, mostly from natural increase rather than immigration.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Most Acadian women in the 18th century gave birth to living children an average of eleven times.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Although these numbers are identical to those in Canada, 75% of Acadian children reached adulthood, many more than in other parts of New France.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The isolation of the Acadian communities meant the people were not exposed to many of the imported epidemics, allowing the children to remain healthier.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1714, a few Acadian families emigrated to Île Royale.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] But for the majority of Acadians, they could not be enticed by the French government to abandon their family lands for an area which was unknown and uncultivated.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Some Acadians migrated to nearby Île Saint-Jean (now Prince Edward Island) to take advantage of the fertile cropland.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In 1732, the island had 347 settlers but within 25 years its population had expanded to 5000 Europeans.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Much of the population surge on Île Saint-Jean took place in the 1750s, as Acadians left during the rising tensions on peninsular Nova Scotia after the settlement of Halifax in 1749.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Le Loutre played a role in these removals through acts of encouragement and threats.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The exodus to Île Saint-Jean became a flood with refugees fleeing British-held territory after the initial expulsions of 1755.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In contemporary Atlantic Canada, it is estimated that there are 300,000 French-speaking Acadians.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In addition, there is a diaspora of over three million Acadian descendants in the world, primarily in the United States, in Canada outside the Atlantic region, and in France.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Most Acadian households were self-sufficient, with families engaged in subsistence farming only for a few years while they established their farms.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Very rapidly the Acadians established productive farms that yielded surplus crops that allowed them to trade with both Boston and Louisbourg.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Farms tended to remain small plots of land worked by individual families rather than slave labor.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The highly productive dyked marshlands and cleared uplands produced an abundance of fodder that supported significant production of cows, sheep and pigs.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Farmers grew various grains: wheat, oats, barley, hops and rye; vegetables: peas, cabbage, turnips, onions, carrots, chives, shallots, asparagus, parsnips and beets; fruit: apples, pears, cherries, plums, raspberry and white strawberry.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] In addition they grew crops of hemp and flax for the production of cloth, rope, etc.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] From the rivers, estuaries and seas they harvested shad, smelts, gaspereau, cod, salmon, bass, etc., utilizing fish traps in the rivers, weirs in the inter-tidal zone and from the sea with lines and nets from their boats.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Charles Morris observed the Acadians at Minas hunting beluga whales.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The Acadians also varied their diets by hunting for moose, hare, ducks and geese, and pigeon.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] After 1630, the Acadians began to build dikes and drain the sea marsh above Port Royal.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The high salinity of the reclaimed coastal marshland meant that the land would need to sit for three years after it was drained before it could be cultivated.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] The land reclamation techniques that were used closely resembled the enclosures near La Rochelle that helped make solar salt.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] As time progressed, the Acadian agriculture improved, and Acadians traded with the British colonies in New England to gain ironware, fine cloth, rum, and salt.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] During the French administration of Acadia, this trade was illegal, but it did not stop some English traders from establishing small stores in Port Royal.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Under English rule, the Acadians traded with New England and often smuggled their excess food to Boston merchants waiting at Baie Verte for transshipment to the French at Louisbourg on Cape Breton Island.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Many adult sons who did not inherit land from their parents settled on adjacent vacant lands to remain close to their families.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] As the Acadian population expanded and available land became limited around Port Royal, new settlements took root to the northeast, in the Upper Bay of Fundy, including Mines, Pisiquid, and Beaubassin.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/acadia] Many of the pioneers into that area persuaded some of their relatives to accompany them, and most of the frontier settlements contained only five to ten interrelated family units.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The **Agadir Crisis**, **Agadir Incident**, or **Second Moroccan Crisis**, was a brief crisis sparked by the deployment of a substantial force of French troops in the interior of Morocco in July 1911 and the deployment of the German gunboat SMS *Panther* to Agadir, a Moroccan Atlantic port.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Germany did not object to France's expansion but demanded "territorial compensation" for itself.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Berlin threatened warfare, sent a gunboat and stirred up German nationalists.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Negotiations between Berlin and Paris resolved the crisis on 4 November 1911: France took over Morocco as a protectorate in exchange for territorial concessions to German Cameroon from the French Congo.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] In Britain, David Lloyd George, then Chancellor of the Exchequer, made a dramatic "Mansion House" speech on 20 July 1911—with the consent of prime minister H.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Asquith and Foreign Secretary, Sir Edward Grey, bypassing the non-interventionist majority in the Cabinet—that denounced the German move as an intolerable humiliation.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] There was talk of war and Germany backed down; relations between Berlin and London worsened and the British moved closer to France.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Berlin felt humiliated and began to realise that it was operating with few allies and antagonising multiple potential adversaries.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] France's pre-eminence in Morocco had been upheld by the 1906 Algeciras Conference, following the First Moroccan Crisis of 1905–06.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] France and Germany agreed on 9 February 1909 that while France would have exclusive political control, the two nations would uphold each other's economic interests in Morocco.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] In 1911 they forced the sultan to sign a new treaty wherein he promised not to sign any other treaties without French approval, arguably violating the earlier made agreements.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Germany's move was aimed at testing the relationship between Britain and France, and possibly intimidating Britain into an alliance with Germany.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Germany was also enforcing compensation claims for acceptance of effective French control of Morocco.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] In 1911, a rebellion broke out in Morocco against Sultan Abd al-Hafid.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The French—after forcing the Sultan to request their assistance—prepared to send troops to help put down the rebellion under the pretext of protecting European lives and property in Fèz.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Actual danger to European communities was remote: the rebellion broke out deep in the interior.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] They dispatched a flying column at the end of April.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] On 8 June, the Spanish deployed troops to occupy Larache and Ksar el-Kebir, fearing a French annexation of the country.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Joseph Caillaux, then French minister for Finance, assured German diplomats in May 1911 that "France would be prepared, if the Germans recognised its vital interest in Morocco, to make concessions elsewhere".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] On 19 June, France agreed to start negotiations.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] After ten days, they still had not responded.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] It was then that Kiderlen-Waechter, the German Foreign Minister, asked Kaiser Wilhelm II for permission to send a gunboat, having rejected the need to send two ships out of belief that the French would be quickly willing to negotiate.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] On 1 July, the German gunboat SMS *Panther* arrived at the port of Agadir, under the pretext of protecting German trade interests.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The larger *Bremen*-class cruiser SMS *Berlin* came days later, replacing the gunboat.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] A German civilian, Hermann Wilberg, 110 kilometres (70 mi) to the north, was sent south to Agadir to provide a pretext for the arrival of the *Panther*, but he only reached Agadir three days after the ship had arrived.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] There was an immediate reaction from the French and the British.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] In the midst of this crisis, Germany was hit by financial turmoil.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The stock market plunged by 30 percent in a single day, the public started cashing in currency notes for gold, and there was a run on the banks.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The Reichsbank lost a fifth of its gold reserves in one month.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] It was rumoured that the French finance minister had orchestrated this crisis.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Faced with the possibility of being driven off the gold standard, the Kaiser backed down and let the French take over most of Morocco.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The German terms, as presented on 15 July, while containing an offer to cede the northern part of Kamerun and Togoland, demanded from France the whole of the French Congo from the Sangha River to the sea, to which was later added the transfer of France's right to the preemption of the Belgian Congo.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] This 275,000 km2 (106,000 sq mi) territory, known as Neukamerun, became part of the German colony of Kamerun.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The area is partly marshland (where sleeping sickness was widespread) but gave Germany an outlet on the Congo River.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Germany ceded to the French colony of Tchad a small area of territory to the southeast of Fort Lamy (now part of Chad).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] French premier Caillaux's negotiations with the Germans were leaked, causing him to fall from office on 21 January 1912, after a term of only seven months.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] In Germany, the Franco-German accord was also criticised—especially by the nationalist press—for giving Germany too little.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The initial reaction in London was cautious: the Liberal government in Cabinet felt that France was largely responsible for triggering the crisis and ought therefore be urged to give ground.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The British government attempted to restrain France from adopting hasty measures and to dissuade her from sending troops.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] In April, the Foreign Secretary Sir Edward Grey wrote: "what the French contemplate doing is not wise, but we cannot under our agreement interfere".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] When Cabinet authorised Grey to inform the French that Britain might accept a German presence in Morocco on 19 July, the French government replied angrily that any such acceptance would breach the 1904 Anglo-French Agreement.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The prospect of a German naval port on the Atlantic, however, allowed Grey to secure Cabinet's approval on 21 July to inform the German ambassador that Britain would respond forcefully to defend its interests.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Britain sent battleships to Morocco, in case war broke out.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] As in the First Moroccan Crisis, British support of France showed the strength of the Entente Cordiale.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Divisions, however, became clear between the supporters of the entente (Grey, Lloyd George and Asquith especially) and the non-interventionists (who made up a majority of the Cabinet).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Lloyd George delivered the Mansion House speech on 21 July 1911, bypassing the Liberal non-interventionists in Cabinet.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Viscount Morley, secretary of state for India, denounced the speech as an 'unwarranted and unfortunate provocation to Germany'; Lord Loreburn, the Lord Chancellor, entreated Grey to take a non-interventionist stance and disavow the speech.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Later in the year, there was a backbench revolt against Grey, which was unsuccessful.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Kissinger labels the risk-taking in this crisis used to appease the nationalism-inclined journalists and agitated public while disregarding the true interests at stake elsewhere as "strategic frivolity".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The crisis seems comic—its obscure origin, the questions at stake, the conduct of the actors—indeed was comic.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] With Sultan Abd al-Hafid's capitulation and signing of the Treaty of Fes (30 March 1912), France established a full protectorate over Morocco, ending what remained of that country's formal independence.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] British backing of France during the crisis reinforced the Entente between the two countries (and with Russia as well), increasing Anglo-German estrangement, deepening the divisions which would culminate in the First World War.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] This incident led Britain's Home Secretary Winston Churchill to conclude the Royal Navy must convert its power source from coal to oil, to preserve its supremacy.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Until then, the locally abundant coal was favoured over imported oil (mostly from Persia), but the speed and efficiency offered by oil convinced him that "Mastery itself was the prize of the venture." Subsequently, Churchill was asked by Prime Minister H.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Asquith to become First Lord of the Admiralty, which he accepted.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The crisis led Britain and France to conclude a secret naval agreement by which the Royal Navy promised to protect the northern coast of France from German Navy attack, while France concentrated her fleet in the western Mediterranean and agreed to defend British interests there.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] France was thus able to guard her communications with her North African colonies, and Britain to concentrate more force in home waters to oppose the German High Seas Fleet.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Britain also formed a Railway Executive Committee in order to rapidly mobilise in the event of a continental war.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] German world historian Oswald Spengler was inspired by the episode to write his *The Decline of the West*.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] During the First World War, in 1916, Neukamerun returned to France.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] The territory today forms part of Chad, Central African Republic, the Republic of the Congo, and Gabon.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/agadir-crisis] Established in 1912, the French protectorate in Morocco lasted until 1956.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The **Alaska boundary dispute** was a territorial dispute between the United States and the British Empire over the Canada–United States border regarding Alaska between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] As Canada was then a British dominion, the United Kingdom held the responsibility of negotiating with the American government over the dispute, which had existed since 1825 between Britain and Russia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Following the United States' acquisition of Alaska from Russia in 1867, the Canada–Alaska border continued to be disputed, which intensified following the 1897 Klondike Gold Rush in Yukon.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Eventually, Anglo-American negotiations led to the dispute being resolved by arbitration in 1903.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The final resolution favored the American position, as Canada did not get an all-Canadian outlet from Yukon's gold fields to the Pacific Ocean.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] News of the dispute's outcome was met with widespread anger in Canada, which viewed the British government as betraying them by prioritizing better Anglo-American relations over Canadian interests.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] In 1825 Russia and the United Kingdom signed a treaty to define the borders of their respective colonial possessions, the Anglo-Russian Convention of 1825.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] This part of the treaty language was an agreement on general principles for establishing a boundary in the area in the future, rather than any exact demarcated line.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Signed in 1839, the RAC–HBC Agreement created an understanding between the Russian-American Company and the Hudson's Bay Company.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The lease was renewed until the end of Russian America.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] This lease was later brought up by the Province of British Columbia as bearing upon its own territorial interests in the region, but was ignored by Ottawa and London.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The United States bought Alaska in 1867 from the Russian Empire in the Alaska Purchase, but the boundary terms were ambiguous.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] In 1871, British Columbia united with the new Dominion of Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The Canadian government requested a survey of the boundary, but the United States rejected it as too costly; the border area was very remote and sparsely settled, and without economic or strategic interest.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] In 1898, the national governments agreed on a compromise, but the government of British Columbia rejected it.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] President McKinley proposed a permanent lease to Canada of a port near Haines, but Canada rejected that compromise.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] In 1897–98 the Klondike Gold Rush in Yukon, Canada, enormously increased the population of the general area, which reached 30,000, composed largely of Americans.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Some 100,000 fortune seekers moved through Alaska to the Klondike gold region.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] From a population of 500 in 1896, the village's population grew to approximately 17,000 people by summer 1898.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The presence of gold and a large new population greatly increased the importance of the region and the desirability of fixing an exact boundary.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Canada wanted an all-Canadian route from the gold fields to a seaport.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] There were reports that Canadian citizens were harassed by the United States as a deterrent to making any land claims.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The head of Lynn Canal was the main gateway to the Yukon, and the North-West Mounted Police (NWMP) sent a detachment to secure the location for Canada.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] This was based on Canada's assertion that that location was more than ten marine leagues from the sea, which was part of the 1825 boundary definition.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] A massive influx of American stampeders through Skagway very quickly forced the Canadian police to retreat.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] They set up posts on the desolate summits of Chilkoot and White Passes.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] This was still disputed territory, as many Americans believed that the head of Lake Bennett, another 12 miles (19 km) north, should be the location of the border.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] To back up the police in their sovereignty claim, the Canadian government also sent the Yukon Field Force, a 200-man Army unit, to the territory.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The soldiers set up camp at Fort Selkirk so that they could be fairly quickly dispatched to deal with problems at either the coastal passes or the 141st meridian west.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The posts set up on the passes by the NWMP were effective in the short term, as the provisional boundary was accepted, if grudgingly.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] In September 1898, serious negotiations began between the United States and Canada to settle the issue, but those meetings failed.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The treaty of 1825 had been drawn up in French, and the 1903 British advocates discussed the exact meaning of words like "*côte*/coast", "*lisière*/strip" and "*crête*/crest".
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The maps of George Vancouver, which were used as a fixing line by the commission of 1825, showed a continuous line of mountains parallel to the coast — however, the mountain range is neither parallel to the coast nor continuous.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Jette, Lieutenant Governor of Quebec; and Allen B.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Aylesworth, K.C., from Toronto), and one Briton (Baron Alverstone).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Armour, the Chief Justice of Ontario, who died in London on July 11, 1903, while working on the boundary commission.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] All sides respected Root, but he was a member of the U.S.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Canadians ridiculed the choice of the obscure ex-Senator Turner and, especially, Lodge, a leading historian and diplomatic specialist whom they saw as unobjective.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The British member Lord Alverstone sided with the U.S. position on these basic issues.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The agreed demarcation line was a compromise falling roughly between the maximal U.S. and maximal Canadian claim.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The "BC Panhandle" (the Tatshenshini-Alsek region) was not quite exclaved from the rest of British Columbia.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Keenlyside concluded, "The Americans, of course, did have the better case." He judged that most of the tribunal's decisions were fair.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] This was one of several concessions that Britain offered to the United States (the others being on fisheries and the Panama Canal).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] It was part of a general policy of ending the chill in Britain–U.S. relations, achieving rapprochement, winning American favor, and resolving outstanding issues (the Great Rapprochement).
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] The Canadian judges refused to sign the award, issued on 20 October 1903, due to the Canadian delegates' disagreement with Lord Alverstone's vote.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Canadians protested the outcome, not so much the decision itself but that the Americans had chosen politicians instead of jurists for the tribunal, and that the British had prioritized better Anglo-American relations over Canadian interests.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] This led to a wave of anger at Britain throughout Canada as well as a surge in Canadian nationalism as separate from an imperial identity.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Although suspicions of the U.S. provoked by the award may have contributed to Canada's rejection of a free trade with the United States in the 1911 "reciprocity election", historian F.
[src:alaska-boundary-dispute/alaska-boundary-dispute] Gibson concluded that Canadians vented their anger less upon the United States and "to a greater degree upon Great Britain for having offered such feeble resistance to American aggressiveness.
